<Base
  title="MODUS · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="A linguistics question with a language model for a laboratory: is modal force a quantification over a set of possible worlds (Kratzer) or a single degree of certainty (Lassiter)? The Master's thesis."
  toc={true}
>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Modal force · thesis flagship · pilot run
    </div>
    <h1>MODUS — what is modal force made of?</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      When a system handles <em>must</em> and <em>might</em>, is its representation of modal force a
      quantification over a <strong>set of possible worlds</strong> (Kratzer), or a single
      <strong>degree of certainty</strong> (Lassiter)? A linguistics question, with a language model
      for a laboratory — and my Master's thesis.
    </p>

    <p>
      MODUS studies the <strong>semantics of modal force</strong>; the language model is the
      <strong>instrument</strong>, not the object. The move it turns on is that the competing analyses
      are <strong>empirically underdetermined by the usual evidence</strong>: Kratzer-style
      quantification over a world-set and Lassiter-style degree semantics predict the <em>same</em>
      truth-value judgments and entailment patterns for most sentences. Judgment data cannot separate
      them — which is exactly the gap a model can fill.
    </p>

    <h2>Why a language model is a legitimate instrument for a semantic question</h2>
    <p>Two things the LM offers that neither judgment data nor human subjects can:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>A new kind of evidence — representational <em>format</em> under causal intervention.</strong>
        In a system that reproduces the modal behaviour, you can ask whether the internal
        representation carries a <strong>set</strong> (competitor identity, duality geometry, exclusion
        structure) or only a <strong>scalar</strong> — and <em>ablate</em> it to test whether the
        behaviour needs it. Judgment data is blind to format; you cannot ablate a representation in a
        person.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>A pure language-only learner.</strong> For the emergence question, the LM isolates the
        limiting case — a system with <em>only</em> linguistic input — so a result about when force
        appears is evidence about <em>what language can carry</em>, a claim about language, not about
        one network.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2>The honest bridge — what an LM result licenses, and what it does not</h2>
    <p>
      A finding in one trained network is not automatically a fact about modality as such. The bridge
      bounds every stage's claim:
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      MODUS's licensed statements are about <strong>format sufficiency and learnability</strong> — what
      representational format is <em>enough</em> to support the modal behaviour, and whether it is
      inducible from language alone — <strong>not</strong> about the human ground-truth semantics of
      English modals.
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      This is still a <strong>linguistics</strong> contribution: it constrains theories by parsimony
      and learnability (a theory positing structure the behaviour demonstrably does not need is, as an
      account of <em>this</em> competence, weaker), and it turns a debate that was underdetermined into
      one with a new, causal source of evidence. It just does not claim to read human semantics off a
      model.
    </p>

    <h2>Four stages, serving one question</h2>
    <p>Each stage is only well-posed if the one above it passed.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>pilot</strong> — <em>Is modal force representationally real and load-bearing, or an
        epiphenomenon of surface lexis?</em> &nbsp;→ a force direction <code>D</code> plus causal
        ablation, with a base-rate control <code>D′</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>FORMA</strong> — <em>Is the format sets/worlds (Kratzer) or degrees (Lassiter)?</em>
        &nbsp;→ competitor-set decodability, duality geometry, exclusion (dis)continuity.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>GRADUS</strong> — <em>Is the certainty axis threshold or continuous — the graded form
        of the same debate?</em> &nbsp;→ a constructed graded-force ruler + calibration test.
        <span class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Its own page:
        <a href="/research/gradus">GRADUS — a graded ruler for modal force</a>.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Stage 2</strong> — <em>Can modal force be induced by linguistic input alone, and under
        what input?</em> &nbsp;→ the same instrument across training checkpoints / controlled corpora.
        This is the thesis's forward edge.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Status</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Pilot — done (a smoke test, not yet a finding).</strong> Qwen2.5-0.5B, one evidence
      family: a force direction <code>D</code> is built from evidence alone, with no modal word
      present; ablating it while the model answers a <em>might</em> item raises that item's certainty
      by <strong>+0.152</strong>, while ablating a base-rate control <code>D′</code> does nothing
      (−0.033) — the predicted structure signature, with the confound behaving correctly.
    </p>
    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">
      Honest caveats that keep it a smoke test: the ablation <em>overshoots</em> (might ends above the
      must level, so "moves toward must" is loose); the must–might baseline gap is small (0.063); and a
      norm-matched random-direction control is still needed to exclude generic disruption. Next: that
      control, scale-up, and 2–3 more evidence families for convergence — then <strong>FORMA</strong>,
      the sets-vs-degrees test.
    </p>

    <h2>Scope &amp; claim discipline</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Epistemic force only</strong> — <em>must</em> / <em>might</em> as evidence-licensed
        inference (von Fintel &amp; Gillies 2010), not logical necessity.</li>
      <li>ML vocabulary stays <strong>instrument</strong> vocabulary; the theoretical claim is about the
        semantics and learnability of modal force, never "the model understands modality".</li>
      <li>No claim about humans: convergence ≠ homology. Primary venues are semantics-side (SALT,
        <em>Semantics &amp; Pragmatics</em>, Sinn und Bedeutung, IWCS); interpretability venues are a
        secondary, methods-facing outlet.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
</Base>
